            "230: Checkpoints are the mechanism with which git-ai captures human vs AI changes. ",
            "231: A checkpoint is a diff between previously captured file contents and the file contents at the new checkpoint, with an attribution to either a human or AI author. ",
            "234: Checkpointing occurs at the boundary between human and AI changes. ",
            "235: When an AI tool uses a fileEdit command, it will fire a preToolUse hook, initiating a human checkpoint. All file changes detected during this checkpoint will be attributed to the human developer. ",
            "236: This captures all previous human changes before AI tools begin making changes. ",
            "238: Then, a postToolUse hook is fired after the AI tool completes editing. This initiates an AI checkpoint and attributes changes made by the AI during that fileEdit command. ",
            "240: Checkpoint metadata is persisted, then placed into the change_history field in the metadata section. ",
            "242: You can see a visualization at https://usegitai.com/docs/cli/how-git-ai-works#part-1-what-happens-on-a-developers-machine",
            "245: #### Prompt association",
            "246: For AI checkpoints, the prompt that generated the fileEdit will be saved. ",
            "247: This results in a 1 to N relationship between prompts and checkpoints, as a single prompt can lead to multiple fileEdits.",
            "248: ",
            "249: ",
            "250: #### What files are compared during checkpointing",
            "251: A checkpoint only diffs file contents for tracked files. "
          ],
